Create an IAM role as below:

1) IAM role name must be iamrole_mark.

2) Entity type must be AWS Service and use case must be EC2.

3) Attach a policy named iampolicy_mark.

Steps Using AWS Console:
1. Login to AWS Console:
Go to the AWS Management Console.
Log in with your credentials.
2. Navigate to IAM Service:
In the search bar at the top, type IAM and select IAM from the list of services.
3. Create a New IAM Role:
In the left sidebar, click on Roles.
Click the Create role button.
4. Select Entity Type and Use Case:
Under Select type of trusted entity, choose AWS service.
In the Choose a use case section, select EC2 (this allows the role to be assumed by EC2 instances).
Click Next: Permissions.
5. Attach the Policy:
In the Attach permissions policies section, search for iampolicy_mark.
Check the box next to the iampolicy_mark policy to attach it to the role.
6. Review and Create the Role:
Role name: Enter iamrole_mark as the role name.
Add an optional description if needed.
Review the role details and click Create role.

Steps Using AWS CLI:
1. Create the IAM Role:
To create the IAM role iamrole_mark with the appropriate permissions for EC2 and attach the policy iampolicy_mark, run the following AWS CLI command:

aws iam create-role --role-name iamrole_mark --assume-role-policy-document file://ec2-trust-policy.json --region us-east-1

2. Attach the Policy to the Role:
After the role is created, attach the iampolicy_mark policy to the iamrole_mark role with the following command:
aws iam attach-role-policy --role-name iamrole_mark --policy-arn arn:aws:iam::aws:policy/iampolicy_mark --region us-east-1

3. Verify the Role and Policy Attachment:
To verify that the role has been created and the policy is attached, you can run the following command:
aws iam get-role --role-name iamrole_mark --region us-east-1
